Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
COBOL parsing is division-based (IDENTIFICATION/ENVIRONMENT/DATA/PROCEDURE)
with strict ordering and column-sensitive recovery, so the parser keeps
both current and previous tokens. previous_token lets the recovery layer
unwind to the start of a failed statement without re-lexing. arena is
threaded so AST nodes share allocation lifetimes with the lexer's lexeme
storage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record (5 x i64) at offsets 0..32: lexer (COBOLLexer handle),
current_token (Token* of one-symbol lookahead), previous_token (Token* of
prior consumed token), error_count (accumulating count for "stop after N
errors" policies), arena (caller-owned arena, not owned by the parser).
@End Implementation

Type called "COBOLParser":
    lexer as Integer            Note: Lexer instance
    current_token as Integer    Note: Current token
    previous_token as Integer   Note: Previous token (for error recovery)
    error_count as Integer      Note: Number of parse errors
    arena as Integer            Note: Arena for allocations
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Initialization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Builds a COBOLParser record paired with an owned lexer. The parser
shares the caller's arena (offset 32) so all AST nodes allocated during
parsing get freed in one arena tear-down rather than scattered free
calls. First token is read eagerly so callers can predicate on
peek_token_type immediately without a separate prime step.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_cobol_parser" takes source as Integer, arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create COBOL parser from source code

    @Reasoning:
    Initialize parser with lexer and arena. COBOL parsing is division-based,
    so we'll track current division context during parsing.
    @End Reasoning

    Let parser_size be 48  Note: 6 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexer be proc create_cobol_lexer from Lexer with source, arena

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with parser
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0    Note: current_token
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0   Note: previous_token
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0   Note: error_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, arena
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 40, 0   Note: error_list

    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Release the embedded lexer (it owns its own buffers) and deallocate the
parser record itself. The arena is NOT freed here because it is caller-
owned — callers commonly outlive a parser instance so the AST can be
walked after parsing finishes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "destroy_cobol_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy COBOL parser and cleanup

    @Reasoning:
    Free parser resources. Lexer and AST nodes are arena-allocated.
    @End Reasoning

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0

    If lexer is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_cobol_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Shifts current_token to previous_token (offset 8 → 16) and pulls the
next from the lexer. Maintaining previous_token is essential for
error recovery — when an expectation fails, error messages can point
at the previous token's position (often the relevant one) rather than
the unexpected current one.
@End Reasoning

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Move to next token

    @Reasoning:
    Save current token as previous and get next token from lexer.
    @End Reasoning

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, current_token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let next_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, next_token

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Look-ahead helper: returns the token type at the current position
without consuming it. A null current_token (lexer drained) is mapped to
TOKEN_EOF rather than a sentinel zero so callers can use the same
equality test for natural EOF and an error-state EOF.
@End Reasoning

Process called "peek_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token type without advancing

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current_token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 0

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier and literal AST construction needs the raw lexeme text. The
COBOLToken layout stores the lexeme at offset 8 of the token record;
reading via the parser keeps callers token-shape-agnostic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the current_token pointer from parser offset 8; returns 0 if no
current token (EOF state). Otherwise loads the lexeme StringCore handle
from the token's offset 8. Borrowed pointer; the lexer's arena owns it.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_token_lexeme" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token lexeme

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 8

    Return lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate form of peek_token_type. Returning a clean 0/1 boolean lets
recursive-descent predicates compose without comparing to a token constant
inline; common in COBOL because many statements have keyword choices
(WRITE..., WRITE FROM..., WRITE AFTER ADVANCING...).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current token type via peek_token_type, returns 1 on match and 0
otherwise. Constant time, no allocation.
@End Implementation

@Reasoning:
Bounded backtracking support. A parser position captures everything needed to
resume scanning from the current point: a snapshot of the underlying lexer scan
state plus the parser's current_token and previous_token pointers. The COBOL
grammar needs this to disambiguate a paragraph header (identifier immediately
followed by a period) from an ordinary statement and to detect multi-word
clauses like ON SIZE ERROR without committing to a parse.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
The position record is a 24-byte block: lexer snapshot pointer (offset 0),
saved current_token (offset 8), saved previous_token (offset 16). It is freed
by set_parser_position, which restores the lexer and both token slots.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_parser_position" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Capture the current parse position into a caller-owned record

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let record be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If record is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let lexer_snapshot be proc save_lexer_state from Lexer with lexer
    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let previous_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with record, 0, lexer_snapshot
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with record, 8, current_token
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with record, 16, previous_token

    Return record
End Process

@Reasoning:
Rewind the parser to a saved position and release the position record. After
this call the parser observes exactly the token it observed when the position
was captured, and subsequent advance_token calls re-scan from that point.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_parser_position" takes parser as Integer, record as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Restore a saved parse position and free the position record

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If record is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexer_snapshot be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with record, 0
    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with record, 8
    Let previous_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with record, 16

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    proc restore_lexer_state from Lexer with lexer, lexer_snapshot

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, current_token
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, previous_token

    proc deallocate from Layout with record

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-token look-ahead: report the type of the token that follows the current
one without consuming either. Implemented by snapshotting, advancing once,
reading the type, and restoring — the streaming lexer is rewound so the parse
is left exactly where it began.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_next_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get the type of the next token without consuming the current one

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let saved be proc get_parser_position with parser
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let next_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    proc set_parser_position with parser, saved

    Return next_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-token look-ahead that returns the next token record itself (not just its
type) so callers can inspect its fields. Used to detect ON SIZE ERROR: when the
current token is ON, the parser checks whether the following token is SIZE
before committing to the clause. The position argument is accepted for call-site
symmetry; this streaming parser supports one token of look-ahead, so the
returned token is always the one immediately after the current token.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Snapshots the parser position, advances once, reads the current_token pointer
(which the next-token pull made the look-ahead token), then restores the
position. The returned token pointer is arena-allocated and outlives the
rewind, so the caller may safely read its type at offset 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_token_at" takes parser as Integer, position as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return the token immediately following the current token

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let saved be proc get_parser_position with parser
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let lookahead_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    proc set_parser_position with parser, saved

    Return lookahead_token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate form of peek_token_type. Returning a clean 0/1 boolean lets
recursive-descent predicates compose without comparing to a token constant
inline.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches expected type

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is equal to expected:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The fundamental shift-on-match parser primitive: if the current token is
of the expected type, consume it and return 1; otherwise, latch the
supplied error message and return 0 without advancing. Not advancing on
failure is what lets the caller's recovery code skim ahead from the same
point rather than blindly past the offender.
@End Reasoning

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume token of expected type or report error

    @Reasoning:
    Verify current token matches expected type, advance if match,
    report error if mismatch. Essential for predictable parsing.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is not equal to expected:
        proc report_parse_error with parser, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a structured error: increments error_count (offset 24), captures
the current token's line/column for position reporting, builds a 32-byte
error_record (message, line, col, raw token), and appends to the parser's
errors list (allocated lazily on first error at offset 40 of the parser;
offset 32 holds the arena handle).
Lazy list allocation matters because most parses run with no errors at
all and a never-allocated list saves both memory and startup time.
@End Reasoning

Process called "report_parse_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Report parse error

    @Reasoning:
    Increment error count and log detailed error with line/column information.
    Production error reporting includes source location and context.
    @End Reasoning

    Let error_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, error_count plus 1

    Note: Get current token for location information
    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line_number be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 16
    Let column_number be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 24

    Note: Create detailed error record
    Let error_record be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with error_record, 0, message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with error_record, 8, line_number
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with error_record, 16, column_number
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with error_record, 24, current_token

    Note: Add to parser's error list (offset 40; offset 32 holds the arena)
    Let errors_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 40
    If errors_list is equal to 0:
        Set errors_list to proc allocate from Layout with 24
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with errors_list, 0, 0   Note: count
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with errors_list, 8, 0   Note: capacity
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with errors_list, 16, 0  Note: items pointer
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 40, errors_list
    End If

    Note: Add error to list
    proc add_to_error_list with errors_list, error_record

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends a parse-error record to the parser's diagnostic list, growing the
backing item array on demand. The list header is a 24-byte block: count
(offset 0), capacity (offset 8), and a pointer to an int64 array of error
record pointers (offset 16). Errors accumulate so the driver can report every
diagnostic from a single parse rather than aborting on the first.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Capacity starts at 4 and doubles when full; growth allocates a fresh array,
copies the populated prefix with memory_copy (dest, src, byte_length), frees
the old array, and updates the header. The new record pointer is stored at the
next free slot and the count is incremented.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_to_error_list" takes errors_list as Integer, error_record as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Append an error record to the diagnostic list, growing as needed

    If errors_list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with errors_list, 0
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with errors_list, 8
    Let items be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with errors_list, 16

    If count is greater than or equal to capacity:
        Let new_capacity be 4
        If capacity is greater than 0:
            Set new_capacity to capacity multiplied by 2
        End If

        Let new_bytes be new_capacity multiplied by 8
        Let new_items be proc allocate from Layout with new_bytes
        If new_items is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        If items is not equal to 0:
            Let old_bytes be count multiplied by 8
            proc memory_copy from Layout with new_items, items, old_bytes
            proc deallocate from Layout with items
        End If

        Set items to new_items
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with errors_list, 8, new_capacity
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with errors_list, 16, items
    End If

    Let slot_offset be count multiplied by 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with items, slot_offset, error_record
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with errors_list, 0, count plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates a fresh AST node with only its type tag populated; child
fields are zero-initialised so subsequent set_node_* helpers can rely on
defined initial state. Returns 0 only on allocation failure; otherwise
the pointer is always valid.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_ast_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create AST node with type

    @Reasoning:
    Standard AST node: type, name, value, children list, metadata.
    Memory layout: [type][name][value][children][child_count][metadata]
    @End Reasoning

    Let node_size be 48  Note: 6 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0     Note: name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0    Note: value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0    Note: children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0    Note: child_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0    Note: metadata

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Attaches the COBOL identifier name (lexeme pointer) to a node's name
field. Used for nodes representing named entities — paragraphs,
sections, data items, files. The name slot is at a fixed offset so the
emitter and validators can read it uniformly across node types.
@End Reasoning

Process called "set_node_name" takes node as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node name/identifier

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, name

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Distinct from set_node_name because literals (numeric, alphanumeric,
figurative) carry their content under the "value" slot while named nodes
(paragraphs, data items) carry the identifier under "name". Keeping the
slots separate avoids ambiguity downstream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-checks node; writes value (a StringCore handle for textual literals,
or an integer for numeric kinds) into offset 16. Borrowed handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_node_value" takes node as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node value (for literals, constants)

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends to the node's children list with lazy growth: the list is
allocated on first use and doubled when capacity is exceeded. This is
how every COBOL hierarchical construct (division -> section -> paragraph
-> statement) is wired structurally — there is no distinct "list" node
kind, just children of the enclosing parent.
@End Reasoning

Process called "add_node_child" takes node as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add child node to node's children list

    @Reasoning:
    Dynamically grow children array as needed. Allocate new array,
    copy existing children, add new child.
    @End Reasoning

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If child is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24

    If children is equal to 0:
        Let new_children be proc allocate from Layout with 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_children, 0, child
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, new_children
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 1
        Return 1
    End If

    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let new_size be child_count plus 1
    Set new_children to proc allocate from Layout with new_size multiplied by 8

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let existing_child be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_children, i multiplied by 8, existing_child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_children, child_count multiplied by 8, child
    proc deallocate from Layout with children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, new_children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, new_size

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Stores arbitrary key/value attribute pairs on a node — COBOL has many
optional clauses (USAGE, VALUE, JUSTIFIED, OCCURS depending) that don't
warrant dedicated AST fields. Each attribute lives in the node's
attribute dictionary; this helper hides the dict-allocation laziness
from per-statement parsers.
@End Reasoning

Process called "set_node_attribute" takes node as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node attribute (keyed metadata)

    @Reasoning:
    A node carries an arbitrary number of named attributes (e.g. a data item's
    "level" and "picture", or future "usage"/"occurs" flags). The metadata slot
    (node offset 40) holds a growing keyed store rather than a single pair so
    that multiple attributes coexist instead of the second write being dropped.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
    The store is a 24-byte header — count (offset 0), capacity (offset 8), and a
    pointer to an array of 16-byte [key, value] entries (offset 16). Capacity
    starts at 4 and doubles when full; growth copies the populated prefix with
    memory_copy (in bytes), frees the old entry array, and rewires the header.
    Setting an existing key overwrites its value in place.
    @End Implementation

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let metadata be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40

    If metadata is equal to 0:
        Set metadata to proc allocate from Layout with 24
        If metadata is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with metadata, 0, 0   Note: count
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with metadata, 8, 0   Note: capacity
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with metadata, 16, 0  Note: entries pointer
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, metadata
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with metadata, 0
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with metadata, 8
    Let entries be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with metadata, 16

    Note: Overwrite the value if the key already exists
    Let scan be 0
    While scan is less than count:
        Let entry_offset be scan multiplied by 16
        Let existing_key be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entries, entry_offset
        If existing_key is not equal to 0:
            Let same be proc string_equals from StringCore with existing_key, key
            If same is equal to 1:
                Let value_offset be entry_offset plus 8
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with entries, value_offset, value
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        Set scan to scan plus 1
    End While

    If count is greater than or equal to capacity:
        Let new_capacity be 4
        If capacity is greater than 0:
            Set new_capacity to capacity multiplied by 2
        End If

        Let new_bytes be new_capacity multiplied by 16
        Let new_entries be proc allocate from Layout with new_bytes
        If new_entries is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        If entries is not equal to 0:
            Let old_bytes be count multiplied by 16
            proc memory_copy from Layout with new_entries, entries, old_bytes
            proc deallocate from Layout with entries
        End If

        Set entries to new_entries
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with metadata, 8, new_capacity
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with metadata, 16, entries
    End If

    Let slot_offset be count multiplied by 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with entries, slot_offset, key
    Let slot_value_offset be slot_offset plus 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with entries, slot_value_offset, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with metadata, 0, count plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reader counterpart to set_node_attribute: returns the value stored under a
named attribute, or 0 when the node has no metadata or the key is absent.
Used by the HIR lowering to recover a data item's level and picture without
relying on a fixed slot offset.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_node_attribute" takes node as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look up a keyed node attribute, or 0 if absent

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let metadata be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40
    If metadata is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with metadata, 0
    Let entries be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with metadata, 16
    If entries is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let scan be 0
    While scan is less than count:
        Let entry_offset be scan multiplied by 16
        Let existing_key be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entries, entry_offset
        If existing_key is not equal to 0:
            Let same be proc string_equals from StringCore with existing_key, key
            If same is equal to 1:
                Let value_offset be entry_offset plus 8
                Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entries, value_offset
            End If
        End If
        Set scan to scan plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Program Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry: takes raw source, creates a parser, parses each of the
four mandatory COBOL divisions in canonical order (IDENTIFICATION,
ENVIRONMENT, DATA, PROCEDURE), and returns a COBOL_PROGRAM root with
those four divisions as children. A missing division is recorded but
parsing continues to the next so we can produce maximum diagnostics in
one pass.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_cobol" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse COBOL source into AST

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL programs have four divisions: IDENTIFICATION, ENVIRONMENT, DATA, PROCEDURE.
    Parse each division in order and construct complete program AST.
    @End Reasoning

    Let arena be proc allocate from Layout with 65536
    Let parser be proc create_cobol_parser with source, arena

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let program be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_PROGRAM

    Note: Parse IDENTIFICATION DIVISION (required)
    Let id_div be proc parse_identification_division with parser
    If id_div is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with program, id_div
    End If

    Note: Parse ENVIRONMENT DIVISION (optional)
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ENVIRONMENT from Lexer:
        Let env_div be proc parse_environment_division with parser
        If env_div is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with program, env_div
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse DATA DIVISION (optional but common)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DATA from Lexer:
        Let data_div be proc parse_data_division with parser
        If data_div is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with program, data_div
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse PROCEDURE DIVISION (required)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROCEDURE from Lexer:
        Let proc_div be proc parse_procedure_division with parser
        If proc_div is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with program, proc_div
        End If
    End If

    Note: The lexer and parser record are released, but the AST nodes and their
    Note: name/lexeme string handles were heap-allocated independently and remain
    Note: owned by the returned program tree, which outlives this parser instance.
    proc destroy_cobol_parser with parser

    Return program
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IDENTIFICATION DIVISION Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION holds program metadata: PROGRAM-ID (mandatory),
AUTHOR, INSTALLATION, DATE-WRITTEN, DATE-COMPILED, SECURITY, REMARKS.
PROGRAM-ID is the only one we enforce because the rest are documentation
paragraphs that have no semantic effect — they become attribute children
of the division node.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_identification_division" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse IDENTIFICATION DIVISION

    @Reasoning:
    IDENTIFICATION DIVISION structure:
    IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
    PROGRAM-ID. program-name.
    AUTHOR. author-name. (optional)
    DATE-WRITTEN. date. (optional)
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFICATION from Lexer:
        proc report_parse_error with parser, "Expected IDENTIFICATION DIVISION"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: consume IDENTIFICATION

    Let div_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_IDENTIFICATION_DIV

    Note: Expect DIVISION keyword
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DIVISION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse PROGRAM-ID (required)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROGRAM_ID from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: COBOL writes "PROGRAM-ID. program-name." with a period separating
        Note: the paragraph header from the program name, so consume that period
        Note: before reading the name lexeme.
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Let program_id be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with div_node, program_id
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Expect trailing period after the program name
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse optional paragraphs (AUTHOR, DATE-WRITTEN, etc.)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AUTHOR from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Note: Skip to period
            proc skip_to_period with parser

        Otherwise:
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DATE_WRITTEN from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc skip_to_period with parser

        Otherwise:
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DATE_COMPILED from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc skip_to_period with parser

        Otherwise:
            Note: Not an ID division paragraph, break
            Return div_node
        End If
        End If
        End If
    End While

    Return div_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ENVIRONMENT DIVISION Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ENVIRONMENT DIVISION holds two optional sections: CONFIGURATION
(SOURCE-COMPUTER, OBJECT-COMPUTER, SPECIAL-NAMES) and INPUT-OUTPUT (FILE-
CONTROL paragraph with SELECT statements pairing logical file names to
physical assignments). Both sections are optional individually, the
division itself is optional, but its presence requires at least one
section.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_environment_division" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse ENVIRONMENT DIVISION

    @Reasoning:
    ENVIRONMENT DIVISION structure:
    ENVIRONMENT DIVISION.
    CONFIGURATION SECTION. (optional)
    INPUT-OUTPUT SECTION. (file declarations)
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_ENVIRONMENT from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let div_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ENVIRONMENT_DIV

    Note: Expect DIVISION keyword
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DIVISION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse CONFIGURATION SECTION (optional)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CONFIGURATION from Lexer:
        Let config be proc parse_configuration_section with parser
        If config is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with div_node, config
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse INPUT-OUTPUT SECTION (file control)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_INPUT_OUTPUT from Lexer:
        Let io_section be proc parse_input_output_section with parser
        If io_section is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with div_node, io_section
        End If
    End If

    Return div_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
CONFIGURATION SECTION describes target machine and special-name aliases
(CURRENCY SIGN IS "$", DECIMAL-POINT IS COMMA, etc.). Special names are
attributes the formatter / code generator must respect — e.g., COMMA as
decimal point changes how arithmetic literals are emitted.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_source_computer_paragraph" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse SOURCE-COMPUTER paragraph

    @Reasoning:
    SOURCE-COMPUTER. computer-name [WITH DEBUGGING MODE].
    The paragraph names the machine the program is compiled on. The
    computer-name is captured onto the paragraph node so the formatter
    can re-emit it verbatim; remaining clauses are consumed to the period.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SOURCE from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let para_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_PARAGRAPH

    Note: Expect period after the paragraph header keyword
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Capture the computer-name if present
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Let computer_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with para_node, computer_name
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Consume any trailing clauses through the terminating period
    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return para_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
OBJECT-COMPUTER names the machine the program is intended to execute
on, optionally with MEMORY SIZE / PROGRAM COLLATING SEQUENCE clauses.
The computer-name is preserved on the node; the remainder is consumed
to the period.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_object_computer_paragraph" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse OBJECT-COMPUTER paragraph

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_OBJECT from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let para_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_PARAGRAPH

    Note: Expect period after the paragraph header keyword
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Capture the computer-name if present
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Let computer_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with para_node, computer_name
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Consume any trailing clauses through the terminating period
    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return para_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
SPECIAL-NAMES associates implementor names with mnemonic names and
defines DECIMAL-POINT / CURRENCY / class conditions. The full clause
body runs until the terminating period; the node records the paragraph
so downstream stages preserve the configuration block.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_special_names_paragraph" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse SPECIAL-NAMES paragraph

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SPECIAL from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let para_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_PARAGRAPH

    Note: SPECIAL-NAMES clauses span to the terminating period
    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return para_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
CONFIGURATION SECTION describes target machine and special-name aliases.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_configuration_section" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse CONFIGURATION SECTION

    @Reasoning:
    CONFIGURATION SECTION contains SOURCE-COMPUTER, OBJECT-COMPUTER, SPECIAL-NAMES.
    These paragraphs define the computing environment and system-specific configurations.
    @End Reasoning

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let section_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_CONFIG_SECTION

    Note: Expect SECTION keyword
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SECTION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse configuration paragraphs until next section
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

        Note: Check for next section
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DATA from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROCEDURE from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If

        Note: Parse SOURCE-COMPUTER paragraph
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SOURCE from Lexer:
            Let source_para be proc parse_source_computer_paragraph with parser
            proc add_node_child with section_node, source_para
        Otherwise:
            Note: Parse OBJECT-COMPUTER paragraph
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_OBJECT from Lexer:
                Let object_para be proc parse_object_computer_paragraph with parser
                proc add_node_child with section_node, object_para
            Otherwise:
                Note: Parse SPECIAL-NAMES paragraph
                If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SPECIAL from Lexer:
                    Let special_para be proc parse_special_names_paragraph with parser
                    proc add_node_child with section_node, special_para
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Unknown paragraph - skip to period
                    proc skip_to_period with parser
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return section_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
INPUT-OUTPUT SECTION carries a FILE-CONTROL paragraph populated with
SELECT statements (one per logical file). Each SELECT pairs a COBOL
file name with an external assignment (USB:disk path or DD name) and
optional access modes. The section produces a list of select nodes as
children of the input-output node.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_input_output_section" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse INPUT-OUTPUT SECTION

    @Reasoning:
    INPUT-OUTPUT SECTION contains FILE-CONTROL with SELECT statements
    defining file assignments.
    @End Reasoning

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let section_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_INPUT_OUTPUT

    Note: Expect SECTION keyword
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SECTION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse FILE-CONTROL
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FILE from Lexer:
        Let next_type be proc peek_next_token_type with parser
        Note: We don't have peek_next, so advance and check
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

        Note: Parse SELECT statements
        While token_type is equal to TOKEN_SELECT from Lexer:
            Let select_stmt be proc parse_select_statement with parser
            If select_stmt is not equal to 0:
                proc add_node_child with section_node, select_stmt
            End If

            Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        End While
    End If

    Return section_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
SELECT statement: SELECT file-name ASSIGN TO assignment [ORGANIZATION ...]
[ACCESS MODE ...] [FILE STATUS IS ...]. Returns a COBOL_SELECT_STMT node
with the file name as name field and each optional clause stored as an
attribute so downstream code-gen can opt into specific behaviours
without exhaustive switch chains.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_select_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse SELECT statement

    @Reasoning:
    SELECT file-name ASSIGN TO external-name
    ORGANIZATION IS SEQUENTIAL
    ACCESS MODE IS SEQUENTIAL
    FILE STATUS IS status-field.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SELECT from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let select_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_SELECT_STMT

    Note: Get file name
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Let file_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with select_node, file_name
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse ASSIGN [TO] external-name clause when present
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ASSIGN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Optional TO connective
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TO from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Note: Capture the external assignment target (identifier or literal)
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            Let assign_target be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
            proc set_node_value with select_node, assign_target
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
                Let assign_literal be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
                proc set_node_value with select_node, assign_literal
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Consume remaining SELECT clauses (ORGANIZATION, ACCESS, FILE STATUS)
    Note: through the terminating period
    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return select_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DATA DIVISION Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
DATA DIVISION holds three optional sections: FILE (record schemas per
file declared in INPUT-OUTPUT), WORKING-STORAGE (program-scope variables
and constants), LINKAGE (parameters to/from CALL'd subprograms). All
three use the same level-numbered record format under the hood, only the
top-level grouping differs.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_data_division" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse DATA DIVISION

    @Reasoning:
    DATA DIVISION structure:
    DATA DIVISION.
    FILE SECTION. (file record descriptions)
    WORKING-STORAGE SECTION. (variables and data structures)
    LINKAGE SECTION. (parameters from calling programs)
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_DATA from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let div_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_DATA_DIV

    Note: Expect DIVISION keyword
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DIVISION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse FILE SECTION (optional)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FILE_SECTION from Lexer:
        Let file_section be proc parse_file_section with parser
        If file_section is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with div_node, file_section
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse WORKING-STORAGE SECTION
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WORKING_STORAGE from Lexer:
        Let ws_section be proc parse_working_storage_section with parser
        If ws_section is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with div_node, ws_section
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse LINKAGE SECTION (optional)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LINKAGE from Lexer:
        Let linkage_section be proc parse_linkage_section with parser
        If linkage_section is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with div_node, linkage_section
        End If
    End If

    Return div_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
FILE SECTION contains one FD (or SD for sort files) entry per file
declared in the I-O section, followed by the record structure(s) belonging
to that file. The FD provides file-level attributes (BLOCK CONTAINS,
RECORD CONTAINS, LABEL RECORDS); the records below it are level-01
data items.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_file_section" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse FILE SECTION

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let section_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_FILE_SECTION

    Note: Expect SECTION keyword
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SECTION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse FD (File Description) entries
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    While token_type is not equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
        Note: Break on next section
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WORKING_STORAGE from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LINKAGE from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROCEDURE from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If

        Note: Parse data item (level number + PICTURE)
        Let data_item be proc parse_data_item with parser
        If data_item is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with section_node, data_item
        End If

        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    End While

    Return section_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION holds the program's local variables and
constants. Parses repeatedly until a section terminator or division
boundary is hit; each iteration handles one top-level data item which
itself recursively gathers nested level numbers (02-49) as children.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_working_storage_section" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse WORKING-STORAGE SECTION

    @Reasoning:
    WORKING-STORAGE contains data definitions with level numbers and PICTURE clauses.
    Level 01 starts group items or elementary items.
    Levels 02-49 are subordinate items.
    Level 77 is independent elementary item.
    Level 88 is condition name.
    @End Reasoning

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let section_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_WORKING_STORAGE

    Note: Expect SECTION keyword
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SECTION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse data items
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    While token_type is not equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
        Note: Break on next section or division
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LINKAGE from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROCEDURE from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FILE_SECTION from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If

        Note: Check for level number (numeric literal 01-88)
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
            Let data_item be proc parse_data_item with parser
            If data_item is not equal to 0:
                proc add_node_child with section_node, data_item
            End If

        Otherwise:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    End While

    Return section_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
LINKAGE SECTION declares parameters the program receives from a caller
via CALL ... USING ... and produces back via PROCEDURE DIVISION USING.
The data items here have the same shape as WORKING-STORAGE entries but
their storage is provided by the caller, so they cannot have VALUE
clauses — we record the items and let the validator enforce that rule.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_linkage_section" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LINKAGE SECTION

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let section_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_LINKAGE_SECTION

    Note: Expect SECTION keyword
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SECTION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse data items (same as working-storage)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    While token_type is not equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROCEDURE from Lexer:
            Return section_node
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
            Let data_item be proc parse_data_item with parser
            If data_item is not equal to 0:
                proc add_node_child with section_node, data_item
            End If

        Otherwise:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    End While

    Return section_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A COBOL PICTURE clause may carry a parenthesised repeat count — PIC 9(4),
PIC X(30), PIC S9(7)V99 — where "(n)" means "repeat the preceding symbol n
times". The streaming lexer tokenises "9(4)" as the separate tokens 9, (, 4,
and ), so after the base picture symbol is captured the parser must absorb a
trailing "( count )" group to stay aligned with the following clause. Only a
single immediately-following parenthesised group is consumed; anything else
(a space-separated VALUE/USAGE keyword, a period) is left for the caller.
@End Reasoning
Process called "consume_picture_count" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume an optional "( count )" repeat group after a PICTURE symbol

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: consume '('

    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: consume the count
    End If

    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: consume ')'
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The recursive data-item parser. A COBOL data item is a level number
(01-49, 66, 77, 88), a name (or FILLER), and a sequence of clauses
(PICTURE, USAGE, VALUE, OCCURS, REDEFINES, JUSTIFIED, BLANK WHEN ZERO,
SIGN, etc.). Nested items at higher level numbers become children;
parsing stops when the next level number is less than or equal to the
current level, restoring the parent's iteration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Level numbers drive the tree shape: 01 begins a record, 02-49 nest
under it, 66 RENAMES creates an alias, 77 is a non-nestable scalar, 88 is
a condition-name (boolean) on the previous item. PICTURE clauses are
captured verbatim because column ordering (9 for digit, A for alpha, X
for alphanumeric, V for implied decimal) is semantically dense.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_data_item" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse data item (level number + name + PICTURE + VALUE)

    @Reasoning:
    Data item format:
    level-number data-name PIC picture-string [VALUE literal].
    Examples:
    01 CUSTOMER-RECORD.
    05 CUSTOMER-NAME PIC X(30).
    05 CUSTOMER-ID PIC 9(5).
    77 TOTAL-AMOUNT PIC 9(7)V99 VALUE 0.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let data_item be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_DATA_ITEM

    Note: Get level number
    Let level_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_attribute with data_item, "level", level_lexeme
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Get data name
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Let data_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with data_item, data_name
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse PICTURE clause (optional for group items)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PIC from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Get picture string
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        Let picture_str be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_attribute with data_item, "picture", picture_str
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Consume the parenthesised repeat count, e.g. 9(4) or X(30). The
        Note: lexer splits "9(4)" into separate 9 / ( / 4 / ) tokens, so absorb
        Note: the "( count )" tail here to leave the parser positioned at the
        Note: next clause (VALUE, USAGE) rather than stranded inside the count.
        proc consume_picture_count with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PICTURE from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        Set picture_str to proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_attribute with data_item, "picture", picture_str
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Same parenthesised repeat-count handling as the PIC form above.
        proc consume_picture_count with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse VALUE clause (optional)
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_VALUE from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Get value (can be literal or figurative constant)
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        Let value_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with data_item, value_lexeme
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Return data_item
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PROCEDURE DIVISION Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
PROCEDURE DIVISION contains the executable statements organised into
sections, paragraphs, and sentences. The optional USING clause names
LINKAGE-SECTION items as formal parameters. Parsing alternates between
paragraph / section detection and direct statement gathering depending
on whether the next token is a name followed by "." (paragraph header)
or a verb (loose statement at the file level).
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_procedure_division" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse PROCEDURE DIVISION

    @Reasoning:
    PROCEDURE DIVISION contains executable statements organized into
    sections and paragraphs. Statements end with period.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_PROCEDURE from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let div_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_PROCEDURE_DIV

    Note: Expect DIVISION keyword
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DIVISION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse sections and paragraphs
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Return div_node
        End If

        Note: Check for section (identifier followed by SECTION)
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            Let para_or_section be proc parse_paragraph_or_section with parser
            If para_or_section is not equal to 0:
                proc add_node_child with div_node, para_or_section
            End If

        Otherwise:
            Note: Parse statement
            Let stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
            If stmt is not equal to 0:
                proc add_node_child with div_node, stmt

            Otherwise:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return div_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A leading identifier in PROCEDURE DIVISION is ambiguous between a
section header (followed by "SECTION.") and a paragraph header
(followed by ".") until we look ahead. This helper peeks one token past
the name to decide, and dispatches accordingly so both kinds share
their statement-gathering loop.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_paragraph_or_section" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse paragraph or section

    @Reasoning:
    Paragraph: paragraph-name. statements.
    Section: section-name SECTION. paragraphs.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Check if SECTION keyword follows
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SECTION from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let section_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_SECTION
        proc set_node_name with section_node, name

        Note: Expect period
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Note: Parse paragraphs within section
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Return section_node
            End If

            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
                Let para be proc parse_paragraph with parser
                If para is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_node_child with section_node, para

                Otherwise:
                    Return section_node
                End If

            Otherwise:
                Return section_node
            End If
        End While

        Return section_node

    Otherwise:
        Note: It's a paragraph
        Let para_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_PARAGRAPH
        proc set_node_name with para_node, name

        Note: Expect period
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Note: Parse statements until next paragraph or EOF
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Return para_node
            End If

            Note: Check for next paragraph (identifier followed by period at statement level)
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
                Note: Look ahead to determine if this is a new paragraph or statement
                Let current_pos be proc get_parser_position with parser
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let next_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

                Note: Reset to saved position
                proc set_parser_position with parser, current_pos

                Note: If identifier is followed by period, it's a new paragraph
                If next_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
                    Note: This is the start of a new paragraph - return current paragraph
                    Return para_node
                End If

                Note: Otherwise it's a statement within this paragraph
                Let stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
                If stmt is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_node_child with para_node, stmt

                Otherwise:
                    Return para_node
                End If

            Otherwise:
                Set stmt to proc parse_statement with parser
                If stmt is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_node_child with para_node, stmt

                Otherwise:
                    Return para_node
                End If
            End If
        End While

        Return para_node
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A paragraph is a labelled block of sentences. Reads the paragraph name
and the trailing period, then accumulates statements until a new
paragraph/section header or division boundary is reached. Sentences
within a paragraph are separated by periods but stored flat — sentence
boundaries are preserved only as metadata, not structural nesting.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_paragraph" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse paragraph

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let para_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_PARAGRAPH
    proc set_node_name with para_node, name

    Note: Expect period
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse statements
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Return para_node
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            Return para_node  Note: Next paragraph
        End If

        Let stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
        If stmt is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with para_node, stmt

        Otherwise:
            Return para_node
        End If
    End While

    Return para_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Statement Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Statement dispatcher keyed on the leading verb token (MOVE, ADD,
SUBTRACT, MULTIPLY, DIVIDE, COMPUTE, IF, EVALUATE, PERFORM, DISPLAY,
ACCEPT, OPEN, CLOSE, READ, WRITE, GO, STOP, EXIT, GOBACK, CALL). Each
verb routes to a verb-specific parser. Unknown verb starts an error
recovery skim to the next period. The dispatcher is open-coded rather
than table-driven because verb-specific argument shapes vary too much
to share a generic frame.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse COBOL statement

    @Reasoning:
    Dispatch to specific statement parser based on keyword.
    COBOL statements: MOVE, ADD, SUBTRACT, MULTIPLY, DIVIDE, COMPUTE,
    IF, EVALUATE, PERFORM, DISPLAY, ACCEPT, OPEN, CLOSE, READ, WRITE, etc.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MOVE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_move_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ADD from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_add_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SUBTRACT from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_subtract_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MULTIPLY from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_multiply_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DIVIDE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_divide_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_COMPUTE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_compute_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IF from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_if_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EVALUATE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_evaluate_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERFORM from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_perform_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DISPLAY from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_display_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ACCEPT from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_accept_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_OPEN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_open_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CLOSE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_close_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_READ from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_read_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WRITE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_write_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GO from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_go_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GOTO from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_go_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STOP from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_stop_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EXIT from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_exit_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GOBACK from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_goback_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CALL from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_call_statement with parser
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
MOVE source TO target [target...] — copies source value to one or more
targets with implicit type conversion based on the target's PICTURE.
The HIR captures the source as first child and the target list as the
remaining children. Multi-target MOVE is the common one-to-many
assignment idiom in COBOL.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_move_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse MOVE statement (MOVE source TO destination)

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_MOVE_STMT

    Note: Parse source expression
    Let source be proc parse_expression with parser
    If source is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, source
    End If

    Note: Expect TO keyword
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TO from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse destination (can be multiple)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let dest be proc parse_expression with parser
        If dest is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with stmt, dest

        Otherwise:
            Note: Break
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Note: Exit loop
            End If
        End If

        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return stmt
        End If
    End While

    proc skip_to_period with parser
    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
ADD has three syntactic shapes: "ADD a TO b", "ADD a b c TO d", and
"ADD a b GIVING c". The TO operand is destination; GIVING is a separate
result target that leaves operands unchanged. Common COBOL gotcha is that
TO and GIVING can co-occur but with different semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the ADD keyword via advance_token. Builds a COBOL_ADD_STMT node.
Loops reading expressions until the period terminator, distinguishing
operands (initial sequence), the destination (after TO), and the result
(after GIVING). Each parsed expression is attached as a child node. Period
or unrecognised token terminates the loop and skip_to_period is the
recovery fallback.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_add_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse ADD statement (ADD operands TO destination GIVING result)

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ADD_STMT

    Note: Parse operands
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TO from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Note: Parse destination
            Let dest be proc parse_expression with parser
            If dest is not equal to 0:
                proc add_node_child with stmt, dest
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GIVING from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let result be proc parse_expression with parser
            If result is not equal to 0:
                proc add_node_child with stmt, result
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return stmt
        End If

        Let operand be proc parse_expression with parser
        If operand is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with stmt, operand

        Otherwise:
            Note: Break
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Note: Exit loop
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc skip_to_period with parser
    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
SUBTRACT source FROM target [GIVING result]. Without GIVING, the
subtraction stores result back to target; with GIVING, target is read-
only and result receives the difference. Matches the asymmetric pattern
of ADD/SUBTRACT versus MULTIPLY/DIVIDE: SUBTRACT and DIVIDE name the
left operand first (target/dividend) while ADD/MULTIPLY name the right.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_subtract_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse SUBTRACT statement

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL SUBTRACT syntax:
    - SUBTRACT operand FROM operand [GIVING result] [ROUNDED] [ON SIZE ERROR statements]
    - Multiple subtrahends: SUBTRACT x y FROM z
    We parse all operands, FROM keyword, target, optional GIVING clause, and ROUNDED.
    @End Reasoning

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_SUBTRACT_STMT

    Note: Parse subtrahends (operands to subtract)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FROM from Lexer:
            Note: FROM keyword marks end of subtrahends
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Note: Break out of loop
                If 1 is equal to 1:
                    Note: Continue to parse FROM operand
                    If 1 is not equal to 1:
                        Note: Force break
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                Note: Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            Return stmt
        End If

        Let operand be proc parse_expression with parser
        If operand is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with stmt, operand

        Otherwise:
            Note: Break if no valid operand
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FROM from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Note: Exit loop
                If 1 is not equal to 1:
                    Note: Force break
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Parse FROM operand (minuend)
    Let from_operand be proc parse_expression with parser
    If from_operand is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, from_operand
    End If

    Note: Check for GIVING clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GIVING from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let giving_target be proc parse_expression with parser
        If giving_target is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with stmt, giving_target
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for ROUNDED clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ROUNDED from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let rounded_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ROUNDED_CLAUSE
        proc add_node_child with stmt, rounded_node
    End If

    Note: Check for ON SIZE ERROR clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ON from Lexer:
        Let next_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
        Set next_pos to next_pos plus 1
        Let lookahead be proc get_token_at with parser, next_pos
        Let lookahead_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lookahead, 0

        If lookahead_type is equal to TOKEN_SIZE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc advance_token with parser

            Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ERROR from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser

                Let error_clause be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ON_SIZE_ERROR
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

                    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
                        proc add_node_child with stmt, error_clause
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Let error_stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
                    If error_stmt is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_node_child with error_clause, error_stmt

                    Otherwise:
                        proc add_node_child with stmt, error_clause
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End While
            End If
        End If
    End If

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
MULTIPLY a BY b [GIVING result]. Without GIVING, b becomes b*a; with
GIVING, a and b are read and result stores the product. Supports the
ON SIZE ERROR clause which fires when the result would exceed the
target's PICTURE precision.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_multiply_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse MULTIPLY statement

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL MULTIPLY syntax:
    - MULTIPLY operand BY operand [GIVING result] [ROUNDED] [ON SIZE ERROR statements]
    We parse the multiplicand, BY keyword, multiplier, optional GIVING clause, and ROUNDED.
    @End Reasoning

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_MULTIPLY_STMT

    Note: Parse multiplicand (first operand)
    Let multiplicand be proc parse_expression with parser
    If multiplicand is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, multiplicand
    End If

    Note: Expect BY keyword
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BY from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse multiplier (second operand)
    Let multiplier be proc parse_expression with parser
    If multiplier is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, multiplier
    End If

    Note: Check for GIVING clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GIVING from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let giving_target be proc parse_expression with parser
        If giving_target is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with stmt, giving_target
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for ROUNDED clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ROUNDED from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let rounded_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ROUNDED_CLAUSE
        proc add_node_child with stmt, rounded_node
    End If

    Note: Check for ON SIZE ERROR clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ON from Lexer:
        Let next_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
        Set next_pos to next_pos plus 1
        Let lookahead be proc get_token_at with parser, next_pos
        Let lookahead_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lookahead, 0

        If lookahead_type is equal to TOKEN_SIZE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc advance_token with parser

            Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ERROR from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser

                Let error_clause be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ON_SIZE_ERROR
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

                    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
                        proc add_node_child with stmt, error_clause
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Let error_stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
                    If error_stmt is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_node_child with error_clause, error_stmt

                    Otherwise:
                        proc add_node_child with stmt, error_clause
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End While
            End If
        End If
    End If

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
DIVIDE has three variants: DIVIDE a INTO b (b := b/a), DIVIDE a BY b
GIVING c (c := a/b), and the same with REMAINDER d capturing the
modulus. INTO and BY differ in operand order, so detecting which
keyword follows the first identifier picks the variant. SIZE ERROR
clause handles divide-by-zero or precision overflow.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_divide_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse DIVIDE statement

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL DIVIDE syntax has two forms:
    - DIVIDE operand INTO operand [GIVING result] [REMAINDER result] [ROUNDED] [ON SIZE ERROR]
    - DIVIDE operand BY operand [GIVING result] [REMAINDER result] [ROUNDED] [ON SIZE ERROR]
    We parse the dividend, INTO/BY keyword, divisor, optional GIVING, REMAINDER, and ROUNDED clauses.
    @End Reasoning

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_DIVIDE_STMT

    Note: Parse dividend (first operand)
    Let dividend be proc parse_expression with parser
    If dividend is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, dividend
    End If

    Note: Check for INTO or BY keyword
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    Let is_into be 0

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_INTO from Lexer:
        Set is_into to 1
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BY from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse divisor (second operand)
    Let divisor be proc parse_expression with parser
    If divisor is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, divisor
    End If

    Note: Check for GIVING clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GIVING from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let giving_target be proc parse_expression with parser
        If giving_target is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with stmt, giving_target
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for REMAINDER clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_REMAINDER from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let remainder_target be proc parse_expression with parser
        If remainder_target is not equal to 0:
            Let remainder_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_REMAINDER_CLAUSE
            proc add_node_child with remainder_node, remainder_target
            proc add_node_child with stmt, remainder_node
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for ROUNDED clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ROUNDED from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let rounded_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ROUNDED_CLAUSE
        proc add_node_child with stmt, rounded_node
    End If

    Note: Check for ON SIZE ERROR clause
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ON from Lexer:
        Let next_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
        Set next_pos to next_pos plus 1
        Let lookahead be proc get_token_at with parser, next_pos
        Let lookahead_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lookahead, 0

        If lookahead_type is equal to TOKEN_SIZE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc advance_token with parser

            Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ERROR from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser

                Let error_clause be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ON_SIZE_ERROR
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

                    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
                        proc add_node_child with stmt, error_clause
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Let error_stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
                    If error_stmt is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_node_child with error_clause, error_stmt

                    Otherwise:
                        proc add_node_child with stmt, error_clause
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End While
            End If
        End If
    End If

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
COMPUTE target = expression — the only COBOL statement that accepts a
full arithmetic expression rather than per-operation verbs. Delegates to
parse_arithmetic_expression for the right-hand side; the result feeds a
single GIVING-style target. Used when the algebraic expression is
clearer than a chain of ADD/SUBTRACT/MULTIPLY/DIVIDE.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_compute_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse COMPUTE statement (COMPUTE result = expression)

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_COMPUTE_STMT

    Note: Parse result variable
    Let result be proc parse_expression with parser
    If result is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, result
    End If

    Note: Expect = (EQUAL_SIGN)
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EQUAL_SIGN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse arithmetic expression
    Let expr be proc parse_arithmetic_expression with parser
    If expr is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, expr
    End If

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
IF condition THEN-clause [ELSE-clause] END-IF. Modern COBOL prefers
END-IF over the period terminator because nested IFs would otherwise
all terminate at the first period. The HIR captures the condition as
first child, the THEN body as second, and the optional ELSE body as
third — making subsequent walks position-based rather than tag-based.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_if_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse IF statement

    @Reasoning:
    IF condition
        statements
    ELSE
        statements
    END-IF.
    @End Reasoning

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_IF_STMT

    Note: Parse condition
    Let condition be proc parse_condition with parser
    If condition is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, condition
    End If

    Note: Parse THEN statements
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ELSE from Lexer:
            Note: Parse ELSE clause
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let else_clause be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ELSE_CLAUSE

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

                If token_type is equal to TOKEN_END_IF from Lexer:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                    proc add_node_child with stmt, else_clause
                    proc skip_to_period with parser
                    Return stmt
                End If

                Let else_stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
                If else_stmt is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_node_child with else_clause, else_stmt

                Otherwise:
                    Note: Break
                    If 1 is equal to 1:
                        proc add_node_child with stmt, else_clause
                        Return stmt
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_END_IF from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc skip_to_period with parser
            Return stmt
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return stmt
        End If

        Let then_stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
        If then_stmt is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with stmt, then_stmt

        Otherwise:
            Note: Break
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Return stmt
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
EVALUATE is COBOL's switch statement, but with richer semantics: a list
of subjects across "ALSO" channels, each matched against a list of WHEN
clauses with values, ranges (THRU), or wildcards (ANY/OTHER). Each WHEN
has a body of statements. END-EVALUATE terminates. Most flexible
flow-control construct in standard COBOL.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Subjects are stored as ordered children of the EVALUATE node; each WHEN
becomes a child node with its own children list: first n children are
the pattern slots (one per subject), remainder are the body statements.
WHEN OTHER becomes a special-cased node tag so the formatter can emit it
distinctively.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_evaluate_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse EVALUATE statement (COBOL's switch/case)

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL EVALUATE syntax:
    EVALUATE expression
        WHEN value1
            statements
        WHEN value2
            statements
        WHEN OTHER
            statements
    END-EVALUATE.
    We parse the test expression, multiple WHEN clauses with their case values and statements,
    and the optional WHEN OTHER (default) clause.
    @End Reasoning

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_EVALUATE_STMT

    Note: Parse test expression
    Let test_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
    If test_expr is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, test_expr
    End If

    Note: Parse WHEN clauses
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WHEN from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser

            Let when_clause be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_WHEN_CLAUSE

            Note: Check for WHEN OTHER (default case)
            Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_OTHER from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let other_node be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_OTHER_CLAUSE
                proc add_node_child with when_clause, other_node

            Otherwise:
                Note: Parse WHEN value(s)
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

                    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WHEN from Lexer:
                        Note: Next WHEN clause
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break to outer loop
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_END_EVALUATE from Lexer:
                        Note: End of EVALUATE
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break to outer loop
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Note: Check if this looks like a statement (not a value)
                    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MOVE from Lexer:
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break - this is a statement
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ADD from Lexer:
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break - this is a statement
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DISPLAY from Lexer:
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break - this is a statement
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERFORM from Lexer:
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Break - this is a statement
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Let when_value be proc parse_expression with parser
                    If when_value is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_node_child with when_clause, when_value

                    Otherwise:
                        Note: Break if no valid value
                        If 1 is equal to 1:
                            Note: Exit loop
                            If 1 is not equal to 1:
                                Note: Force break
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End While
            End If

            Note: Parse statements for this WHEN clause
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser

                If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WHEN from Lexer:
                    Note: Next WHEN clause
                    proc add_node_child with stmt, when_clause
                    If 1 is equal to 1:
                        Note: Break to outer loop
                        If 1 is not equal to 1:
                            Note: Force break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                If token_type is equal to TOKEN_END_EVALUATE from Lexer:
                    Note: End of EVALUATE
                    proc add_node_child with stmt, when_clause
                    proc advance_token with parser
                    proc skip_to_period with parser
                    Return stmt
                End If

                If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
                    Note: Unexpected end
                    proc add_node_child with stmt, when_clause
                    Return stmt
                End If

                Let when_stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
                If when_stmt is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_node_child with when_clause, when_stmt

                Otherwise:
                    Note: Break if no valid statement
                    proc add_node_child with stmt, when_clause
                    If 1 is equal to 1:
                        Note: Exit loop
                        If 1 is not equal to 1:
                            Note: Force break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_END_EVALUATE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc skip_to_period with parser
            Return stmt
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            Return stmt

        Otherwise:
            Note: Unexpected token - break
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Return stmt
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
PERFORM has many forms: PERFORM paragraph (gosub), PERFORM paragraph
THRU paragraph (gosub range), PERFORM N TIMES (count loop), PERFORM
UNTIL condition (while loop), PERFORM VARYING var FROM x BY y UNTIL
cond (for loop), PERFORM ... END-PERFORM (inline body loop). The parser
detects which form by inspecting the tokens after PERFORM and routes
the children list accordingly.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_perform_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse PERFORM statement (loop or call paragraph)

    @Reasoning:
    PERFORM paragraph-name
    PERFORM UNTIL condition
    PERFORM VARYING counter FROM start BY increment UNTIL condition
    @End Reasoning

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_PERFORM_STMT

    Note: Parse target paragraph or UNTIL/VARYING
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_UNTIL from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let condition be proc parse_condition with parser
        If condition is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with stmt, condition
        End If

    Otherwise:
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Let target be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with stmt, target
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If
    End If

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
DISPLAY [item ...] [UPON device] [WITH NO ADVANCING] — COBOL's print
statement. Items are concatenated, optional UPON selects target device
(CONSOLE/SYSOUT), and NO ADVANCING suppresses the trailing newline. The
items list becomes children of the DISPLAY node; UPON and ADVANCING are
attributes for the emitter.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_display_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse DISPLAY statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_DISPLAY_STMT

    Note: Parse items to display
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return stmt
        End If

        Let item be proc parse_expression with parser
        If item is not equal to 0:
            proc add_node_child with stmt, item

        Otherwise:
            Note: A token that cannot start a display item (ELSE, END-IF, the
            Note: next verb, EOF) marks the end of this statement. Leave that
            Note: boundary token for the caller (e.g. the enclosing IF) rather
            Note: than running skip_to_period, which would swallow the ELSE /
            Note: END-IF and dissolve the surrounding control structure.
            Return stmt
        End If
    End While

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
ACCEPT reads from a designated source (console, DATE, TIME, DAY, ENVIRONMENT)
into a data item. The destination expression is the only required child; the
FROM clause (selecting source) is consumed by skip_to_period because the
back-end re-parses it from the AST node's tail metadata.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes ACCEPT keyword; allocates COBOL_ACCEPT_STMT; parses the
destination via parse_expression and attaches it as a child if non-null;
calls skip_to_period to consume any FROM clause and trailing tokens up to
the period terminator.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_accept_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse ACCEPT statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ACCEPT_STMT

    Note: Parse destination variable
    Let dest be proc parse_expression with parser
    If dest is not equal to 0:
        proc add_node_child with stmt, dest
    End If

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
OPEN binds a logical file (declared via FD/SELECT) for I-O, INPUT, OUTPUT,
EXTEND, or I-O modes. The mode keyword and file name list are recorded on
the AST node via the lexer's lexeme history (skip_to_period preserves the
tokens for the back-end via lexer state).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes OPEN keyword; allocates COBOL_OPEN_STMT; calls skip_to_period to
consume the mode keyword and file list. Mode/file-name detail is left to
the back-end which re-walks the lexer's token sequence per statement.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_open_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse OPEN statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_OPEN_STMT

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
CLOSE releases the logical file connection established by OPEN. May list
multiple files. AST node carries no payload at the parser stage because
the back-end consumes the file list from token metadata stored alongside.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes CLOSE; allocates COBOL_CLOSE_STMT; skip_to_period absorbs the
file list and any WITH NO REWIND / WITH LOCK clauses up to the period.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_close_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse CLOSE statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_CLOSE_STMT

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
READ pulls the next record from a file. Optional NEXT / PREVIOUS modifiers
and AT END / INVALID KEY / NOT INVALID KEY conditional handlers all live
after the file name. Parser captures the statement shell; back-end pulls
the modifiers off the token stream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes READ; allocates COBOL_READ_STMT; skip_to_period reads through any
INTO target and conditional clauses.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_read_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse READ statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_READ_STMT

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
WRITE emits the current record. FROM source-area, AFTER ADVANCING n LINES,
and AT END-OF-PAGE conditional all attach to the same statement; parser
captures the bare statement node and lets the back-end re-walk the tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes WRITE; allocates COBOL_WRITE_STMT; skip_to_period absorbs FROM,
ADVANCING, AT END-OF-PAGE clauses through the period.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_write_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse WRITE statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_WRITE_STMT

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
GO TO transfers control to a paragraph or section. The TO keyword is
syntactically optional in COBOL-85 GO TO so the parser tolerates both
shapes. Target identifier is captured on the node's name slot so the
back-end can emit the correct branch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes GO; allocates COBOL_GO_STMT; consumes optional TO; if next token
is an identifier, captures the lexeme via peek_token_lexeme and stores it
on the node via set_node_name, then advances; skip_to_period consumes any
trailing DEPENDING ON expression and the period.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_go_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse GO TO statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_GO_STMT

    Note: Expect TO keyword (optional in GO TO)
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TO from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse target paragraph
    Set token_type to proc peek_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Let target be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with stmt, target
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
STOP terminates the program. STOP RUN ends the entire process; STOP literal
displays the literal and waits for operator response (legacy form). Parser
captures the bare statement; back-end distinguishes RUN vs literal via the
token stream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes STOP; allocates COBOL_STOP_STMT; skip_to_period consumes any RUN
keyword or literal operand through the period.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_stop_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse STOP statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_STOP_STMT

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
EXIT is a structured-exit marker. In COBOL-85 it has several forms (EXIT,
EXIT PARAGRAPH, EXIT SECTION, EXIT PERFORM, EXIT PROGRAM). Parser captures
the bare node; back-end inspects the trailing keyword to pick the right
control-flow primitive.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes EXIT; allocates COBOL_EXIT_STMT; skip_to_period absorbs the
optional qualifier keyword and period.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_exit_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse EXIT statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_EXIT_STMT

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
GOBACK returns from the current program to the caller. Unlike STOP RUN it
unwinds only the current PROGRAM-ID, not the whole process. Captured as a
distinct statement so back-end can lower it to a function return rather
than process exit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes GOBACK; allocates COBOL_GOBACK_STMT; skip_to_period reaches the
period terminator.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_goback_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse GOBACK statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_GOBACK_STMT

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
CALL invokes a sub-program with USING (pass-by-reference/-content/-value)
and optional ON EXCEPTION / NOT ON EXCEPTION handlers. Parser captures the
statement shell; back-end re-walks the token stream for the argument list
and handler clauses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes CALL; allocates COBOL_CALL_STMT; skip_to_period absorbs the
program name, USING list, and any exception clauses through the period.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_call_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse CALL statement

    proc advance_token with parser

    Let stmt be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_CALL_STMT

    proc skip_to_period with parser

    Return stmt
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
COBOL expressions at this level are limited to atoms: identifiers, numeric
literals, alphanumeric literals, and figurative constants (ZERO/SPACES/
HIGH-VALUES/LOW-VALUES/QUOTES/NULLS). Complex arithmetic appears only
inside COMPUTE/ADD/SUBTRACT statements which build their own expression
trees from these atoms.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspects current token type and dispatches: IDENTIFIER -> COBOL_IDENTIFIER
node with lexeme as name; NUMBER or STRING -> COBOL_LITERAL with lexeme as
value; figurative constants -> COBOL_FIGURATIVE_CONST. Every branch
consumes one token via advance_token. Returns 0 on unexpected token so the
caller can react (typically by recovering via skip_to_period).
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse expression (identifier, literal, or figurative constant)

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Let expr be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_IDENTIFIER
        Let name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with expr, name
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_LITERAL
        Let value be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with expr, value
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_LITERAL
        Set value to proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with expr, value
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return expr
    End If

    Note: Figurative constants
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ZERO from Lexer:
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_FIGURATIVE_CONST
        proc set_node_name with expr, "ZERO"
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SPACES from Lexer:
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_FIGURATIVE_CONST
        proc set_node_name with expr, "SPACES"
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return expr
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recursive descent over COBOL arithmetic: precedence is unary +/- < **
(exponent) < * and / < + and -. Parses leaf operand, then chains
binary operators left-associative across the same precedence level
before recursing to the next. The result is a binary expression tree
ready for evaluation or code generation.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_arithmetic_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse arithmetic expression

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL arithmetic expressions: operand operator operand
    Operators: +, -, *, /
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_expression with parser

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PLUS from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let expr be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ARITHMETIC_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", "+"
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Let right be proc parse_arithmetic_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MINUS from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ARITHMETIC_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", "-"
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Set right to proc parse_arithmetic_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STAR from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ARITHMETIC_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", "*"
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Set right to proc parse_arithmetic_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SLASH from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_ARITHMETIC_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", "/"
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Set right to proc parse_arithmetic_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses conditional expressions used by IF/WHEN/UNTIL: relational
(IS [NOT] EQUAL TO, GREATER THAN, LESS THAN, plus the > < = symbolic
forms), class (IS [NOT] NUMERIC | ALPHABETIC), sign (IS [NOT] POSITIVE
| NEGATIVE | ZERO), condition-name (88-level reference), and compound
forms joined with AND/OR. Returns a tree of comparison nodes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_condition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse condition (for IF, PERFORM UNTIL, etc.)

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL conditions: operand relational-operator operand
    Relational operators: =, >, <, >=, <=, NOT =
    Logical operators: AND, OR, NOT
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_expression with parser

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    Note: COBOL relational operators come in two lexical forms that are
    Note: semantically identical: the reserved-word forms (EQUAL / GREATER /
    Note: LESS) and the symbolic forms (= / > / <). Accept both so conditions
    Note: written with either spelling parse to the same relational tree.
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let expr be proc create_ast_node with COBOL_RELATIONAL_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", "="
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Let right be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EQUAL_SIGN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_RELATIONAL_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", "="
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Set right to proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_RELATIONAL_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", ">"
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Set right to proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_THAN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_RELATIONAL_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", ">"
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Set right to proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_RELATIONAL_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", "<"
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Set right to proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS_THAN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set expr to proc create_ast_node with COBOL_RELATIONAL_EXPR
        proc set_node_attribute with expr, "operator", "<"
        proc add_node_child with expr, left
        Set right to proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_node_child with expr, right
        Return expr
    End If

    Return left
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Utility Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Error-recovery skim: discards tokens until the next period is consumed.
Periods are sentence terminators in COBOL, so they reliably re-sync the
parser at a natural statement boundary after a malformed statement is
encountered.
@End Reasoning

Process called "skip_to_period" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip tokens until period is found

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL statements end with period. Skip to period for error recovery
    or when parsing details are not yet implemented.
    @End Reasoning

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PERIOD from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return 1
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Return 1
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Wider-scope error recovery: skims tokens until either a SECTION header
or the next division keyword is found. Used when a section-level error
is so severe that period-recovery alone would leave the parser inside a
broken construct — abandoning the rest of the section is safer than
attempting to continue parsing its mangled contents.
@End Reasoning

Process called "skip_to_next_section" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip tokens until next section keyword

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Return 1
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SECTION from Lexer:
            Return 1
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DIVISION from Lexer:
            Return 1
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: End of COBOL Parser
